        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(openrouter): guard music generation SSE JSON.parse against malformed frames",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n**What problem does this PR solve?**\n\n- Fix classification: Crash-protection for malformed SSE data frames in OpenRouter music generation.\n- Root cause: `processOpenRouterSseLine:128` calls `JSON.parse(data)` on raw SSE `data:` frames without try/catch. The function already handles unrecognized data by returning `false`. A malformed frame throws unhandled `SyntaxError` instead of being skipped.\n- Why this is narrow fix: Wraps the single `JSON.parse` site, returns `false` on failure — same skip path as unrecognized data. The streaming loop continues to the next frame.\n- Patch quality notes: 2 files, +28/-1 lines. v2 adds a regression test: malformed `data: NOT JSON {{{` frame skipped, subsequent valid frame still produces an audio track.\n\n**Why does this matter now?**\n\n- User impact: Malformed SSE frame from OpenRouter audio streaming crashes the entire music generation stream with raw SyntaxError.\n\n**What is intentionally out of scope?**\n\n- Does NOT change: valid SSE frame parsing, audio buffer assembly, stream timeout logic, or the `reader.releaseLock()` in the caller.\n\n**What should reviewers focus on?**\n\n- The new regression test demonstrates the fix end-to-end: malformed frame skipped → valid frame processed → track produced.",
